elements.text: Brian Anderson
Age: 40 Height: 6'1" Lives in: San Diego Job: 911 fire dispatch supervisor
'I know what it's like to feel like there's no hope'
Cost kept him from using GLP-1s, but "I'm glad I didn't. I know I'll be able to sustain my weight loss because of my diet and exercise changes."

Growing up, Brian Anderson was known as Big B: "All my nicknames were size-related." As a high school senior he was more than 400 lbs. and on a liquid diet. By 2019 he'd reached his highest weight, 578 lbs. "Every morning I'd wake up and sit at the edge of the bed for a few minutes. I had to hype myself up to stand up because it was so much," he says. "It's like wearing weight packs everywhere. I was tired all the time. Just walking to my car was a workout." The possibility of hit- ting 600 on the scale was terrifying. "I had to do something." He began by cutting out soda and juice. (Before, "I could knock out a gallon of juice, no problem.") The first 30 lbs. "dropped off," and then COVID hit. While the world was on pause, "it felt like a green light to me." He began walking in his stairwell and doing

outdoor workouts, and he tried a keto diet. "I wasn't exercising before that, so even doing small workouts was super beneficial." He bought a copy of People with a cover story about weight loss. "I was like, 'I'm going to be in that magazine!'" Over the next five years he motivated himself with daily affirmations ("It helps rewire your brain"). Now, at 300 lbs., he's 75 lbs. away from his goal. "I've proven to myself that anything is possible," says Ander- son, who is single and estimates he spends $1,000 monthly on training, healthy food and supplements. As for fulfilling his vow to make it into People, "I'm over the moon. And I want to shed a light for people who feel like they're in the dark. Losing 300 lbs. is daunting, but find one thing you can commit to, and it will be life-changing."

elements.text: ‘Ketamine left me needing a bladder transplant’
AMBER CURRAH, 28, LIVES IN MORECAMBE, LANCASHIRE, WITH HER SIX-YEAR-OLD SON.

Crouched on my bathroom floor, I froze, knowing even a slight movement would make the already unbearable pain worse. Eight hours later, I was finally able to get up. Still in pain, though, I reached for the only thing that would numb it – ketamine.
It was May 2023 and, at 25, I was addicted to the drug. I’d first taken it at a friend’s party, aged 17. It doesn’t mix well with alcohol, and as I’d been drinking, I felt out of control and didn’t like it. But two years later, after my friends encouraged me, I tried it again and it gave me a euphoric feeling. It was easy to get hold of and cost only £15 a bag, so I started taking it socially, three times a week, until I became pregnant at 20.
After I had my son in June 2019, his dad and I co-parented, but I struggled with the responsibility of being a single mum. Any time my son wasn’t with me, I’d take ketamine as a form of escape, to switch off my mind. Initially, there were no side effects, but by 2022 I’d started experiencing problems with my bladder.
I constantly needed a wee, which developed into bouts of immobilising pain. I was referred to a urologist and I admitted I’d used ketamine. She explained that chronic use can shrink the lining of the bladder, which can lead to bleeding and blockages. I measured my liquid intake and discovered my bladder could only hold 20ml, while a normal bladder can hold 500ml.
Although I was horrified, I carried on taking it, but had to stop going out because I was incontinent and in such pain. Eventually, doctors injected hyaluronic acid into my bladder, then attempted to stretch it.
The agony was so horrific, I thought I was going to die. Despite this, I found myself taking more and more ketamine to get the same effect. By January 2023, I was taking it five times a day – I was addicted and couldn’t stop, despite the horrendous pain I was experiencing daily. While my son slept or wasn’t with me, I’d sit in the bath for 10 hours to relieve the pain, and sometimes I’d sleep on the toilet, because I needed a wee constantly. It’s been two years since I stopped taking ketamine, but I’m still living with the consequences and am unable to work because of the constant pain. Every day, I have to get in the bath for two hours to ease it. I still wear incontinence pads and often have to wee in public in the day, because I can’t hold it.

Callum and I only have sex every three months, because I have to make sure I’m not doing much in the following days as I can have increased pain for a week. I’m waiting for an op to remove my bladder and make a new one out of part of my bowels, which I hope will give me a better quality of life.

elements.text: ADVICE
Bossing it
Apprentice star and West Ham United vice-chair KARREN BRADY answers your careers questions

I work for the NHS and have an exit interview coming up, as I'm moving to work in a different hospital. I know this is my opportunity to be transparent with HR as to why I have chosen to leave, but I don't want to burn any bridges. There are many reasons why I'm quitting - including poor management, unprofessionalism and dishonesty among both my peers and superiors - but I'm worried it will come across as spiteful and my comments could get back to the people I worked with. I don't want it to jeopardise having a good reference should I need it in the future, too. Do you have any advice? Vicky

If you're attending an exit interview, you shouldn't have to sugar-coat how you feel. Honesty is important - but how you express it makes all the difference. The goal is to be professional, measured and constructive, not emotional or accusatory. Avoid using overly charged words like "unprofessional", "toxic" or "dishonest". Instead, describe behaviours or patterns that can be addressed constructively. For example, rather than pointing to issues with specific managers, you might say: "At times, I felt there was a lack of clear direction and consistency, which made it difficult for the team to feel supported and confident in priorities." That still tells the truth, but in a way that HR can act on. Frame your points around the impact it had on your experience and ability to perform to the best of your capability. Balance your feedback by also highlighting what you valued about the role or workplace, including the skills you developed, the people you enjoyed working with and the positive experiences you've had. Finally, don't hesitate to ask for confidentiality regarding what you share. Got a careers question for Karren? Email bossingit@fabulousmag.co.uk.
Host of Fabulous podcast No Parental Guidance and mum-of-three LOUISE BOYCE gives you advice from the parenting frontline

My daughter is 15 and has her first boyfriend, who's the same age. He seems nice enough, but her dad and I have said that although he's allowed in her bedroom, the door must stay open - and this means that whenever anyone goes upstairs, they can see in. She is complaining this invades her privacy so is furious, and has said she'll just spend more time at his house as his mum isn't so unreasonable. I don't know his parents at all, and while I don't want to push her away, I also know what teenage hormones are like. Help! Eva

Eva, this is such a familiar and tricky stage, and your instincts to both protect your daughter and respect her budding independence are completely normal. I wish I'd known that my mum meant well when I was 15! At this age, it's healthy for teens to start exploring relationships, but they also need clear boundaries. Asking her to keep the bedroom door open is a reasonable compromise, as it balances her need

for privacy with your need for safety and supervision. It's understandable she feels frustrated - teens often see rules as personal attacks, not safety measures. The key is to communicate calmly, without shaming or lecturing. You could also negotiate some flexibility around shared spaces downstairs, which lets her feel respected. Avoid ultimatums or constant confrontation, and focus on maintaining trust. Listen to her feelings, show interest in her life and model respectful boundaries. While she may test limits, your steady guidance and openness will matter far more in the long-run - she'll know she can come to you if anything ever feels uncomfortable, and that you love her, while allowing her to grow. elements.text: Editorial

Craftsmanship is the watchword for next summer's accessories. Creators of footwear, bags and leather goods emphasised precious details and sophisticated (verging on the 'handmade') fabrications to encourage consumers to buy products that make a very personal statement and, why not, last a little longer than one season. Women's shoes, in particular, will feature plenty of details, ranging from a rich variety of models, materials and heels, so that the most powerful of feminine passions can be given free rein and shoe closets can gain some real gems. Whether ballet shoes, low woven leather sandals or rope flipflops (sometimes with pendants and shells dangling a few centimetres off the ground), the stars of the season will be well-made, stylish yet comfortable shoes. The same goes for mules and clogs in patent leather or transparent rubber, or slingbacks in leather, suede or original patterns such as dappled or Prince of Wales. Here or there, bows or feathers adorn the toes and heels tend to be low across the board, some decorated with stones and crystals. On jewelled sandals, embellished stilettos, and pumps in suede, patent leather or metalized leather, heels are sharper and a little higher. When it comes to details, there is some 'manipulation' of heels, with broken or asymmetric lines, while folding down the rear part of the upper to reveal the heel of the foot is also very interesting. Men's footwear also features some great expertise and attention to detail, introducing innovative models with streamlined lines and a focus on comfort. Classic loafers are joined by suede boots, Franciscan sandals and ultra-soft slippers. When it comes to raw materials, the timeless napa leather and suede feature alongside alternatives such as jute, mesh, canvas and leather woven like the rattan of Thonet chairs. A round of applause has to go to the embroidered trainers, a real must-have for the season.

Coming to bags, as the weather gets warmer, women's bags seem to be getting more and more pliable and roomy. Extremely soft, sometimes embossed, napa folds and draps with ease, accommodating capacity and wearability. Shoppers and sacks, in both leather and fabric, feature mesh, weaving, perforations, openwork, crochet and macramé, while medium sizes, such as bauletto, shoulder and hobo bags, have glossy or brushed surfaces, some embellished with studs, long fringes or beautiful embroidery. That great summer classic, the straw bag, comes in various sizes, for a style suitable for every moment of the holiday, from the beach to the bar. And as the sun goes down, clutches, baguettes
SERGIO ROSSI

and minaudières of every style and shape return, ranging from stripes to leopard, to textures studded with precious stones, flowers or marine details such as corals and shells. Men, as we know, need space and this summer, too, will go for larger bags with an eye for rich materials and quality craftsmanship. Backpacks, large sacks, big bumbags, trunks and shoppers in leather or fabric provide plenty of carrying space, while those content with a smaller bag will be happy with decorated baguettes and original briefcases adorned with paintings or artistic prints.

Finally, summer looks are accessorised with gaudy steel or gold jewellery, such as statement bracelets or chunky earrings, embellished with large stones, crosses or big pendants. One noteworthy detail is a beautiful, intriguing golden snake wrapped around the finger, neck, arm or ear like a terrible boa constrictor.

elements.text: InVOGUE Viewpoint

A Year in
FASHION

It has been 12 months of transformation. From monumental creative shifts and archival revivals to immersive experiences and the challenges facing online luxury, we look back at the defining moments that shaped the industry and set the stage for the season ahead.
Words MAYA MENON
It's all about the experience

As products shift from desire to expectation, luxury brands turn to 'experiential luxury': moments designed to spark emotion, forge connection and leave a lasting impression. Globally, this takes shape in events like Vogue World or Wimbledon, where audiences witness moments in real time. In Singapore, it appears through limited-run experiences such as the Bvlgari Trunk Show at the House of Tan Yeok Nee, Prada Caffé at Ion Orchard, Louis Vuitton × Murakami Pop-up at Joo Chiat and Hermès' Wings of Hermès—public yet fleeting, making them feel like rare, must-see moments.

It has been a year for the books. Looking back at 2025, the spring/summer 2026 season stands out as one of the most pivotal in recent fashion history. Yet beyond the collections, the very machinery of fashion has begun to move in new directions. As we step into 2026, it's worth remembering that 2025 was merely the beginning—the moment when the gears first started to shift. The true outcomes of these changes are only just beginning to unfold.

Some of fashion's most established houses have undergone monumental transformations, from Matthieu Blazy's move to Chanel to Jonathan Anderson's appointment at Dior. These are more than creative shake-ups; they mark cultural turning points. How will the romance of the Chanel woman evolve under Blazy's hand? And how will Anderson's vision reshape Dior's heritage? And beyond this, how will this change the way people aspire and identify with themselves?

It's not just the industry that's changing, audiences are too. It's no longer enough to sell the latest handbag or pair of shoes; people are searching for something that is more resonant, more reflective of the times. There's a growing appetite for exclusivity that extends beyond the things we wear to the experiences we take part in. From Vogue World to Prada Mode, and from global icons like Wimbledon to intimate experiences closer to home—the Bvlgari High Jewellery and Watch Trunk Show at the House of Tan Yeok Nee or the Louis Vuitton x Murakami Pop-up Café at Peranakan House in Joo Chiat—it's all about invoking emotion that runs parallel to the brand itself, allowing people to feel part of it in a deeper, more immersive way.

Needless to say, fashion as we know it, no longer exists the way it once did. As we look back on the year, we distill the shifts, the turning wheels and what lies ahead. These are the eight key moments that have defined the industry this year. ●
The Revival of the Classics

Following this trend, brands are mining their archives for the next must-have accessory. Exclusivity now means pieces that embody uniqueness, heritage, nostalgia and significance. With vintage shopping on the rise, luxury houses are revisiting signature codes and reviving cherished icons. Take Louis Vuitton, for example, which this year reissued Takashi Murakami's iconic candy-dotted collaboration, bringing it back into the spotlight. The allure continues with Chloé's slimmed-down Paddington bag and Céline's east-west Phantom, now featuring a playful smile—both still perfect for a night out.

Kate Winslet wants to age naturally. In a recent interview, the Titanic star, 50, de-nounced the rising popularity of filler and other cosmetic trends, as well as GLP-1s, among her peers. “It is devastating,” she told The Sunday Times. “If a person’s self-esteem is so bound up in how they look, it’s frightening.” Winslet said “all the f**king actresses” who’ve “become obsessed with chasing an idea of perfection” upset her, but not as much as everyday people who “save up for Botox or the s**t they put in their lips.” The Oscar winner is also con-cerned about what’s really in injectables, saying, “The disregard for one’s health is terrifying. It bothers me now more than ever. It is f**king chaos out there.” An irate Winslet even went so far as to point out the lines in her face and hands to prove she “hasn’t got anything” in them. “Some of the most beautiful women I know are over 70,” she added, “and what upsets me is that young women have no concept of what being beautiful actually is.”

elements.text: OPINION
Kate Wills
Our columnist on the trends that have made her delighted to say goodbye to this year
‘From Labubus to Ozempic, why I’m glad 2025 is over’

As it draws to a close, I think we can all agree that 2025 was a strange and difficult year. Like Mummy Pig from Peppa Pig, I spent most of it pregnant, which for me meant nine months of vomiting, acid reflux and elasticated waistbands. But there was at least one good outcome after nine months of misery: Not the birth of my daughter (although she is great), but the fact that I could avoid the year’s most terrifying fashion trend – barrel-leg jeans. Fashion-wise, the last 12 months weren’t really my bag. Perhaps because I didn’t have a weird, snaggle-toothed plush creature hanging from the handle of mine. Labubus were funny for about five minutes, but when grown adults are queueing for cuddly toys – and parting with serious cash – I think we all have to question what the world is coming to. Nothing good it seems, given every conversation I’ve had lately seems to be about how scary AI is (it’s the new “kids and smartphones” chat). The only thing worse than talking about AI is using it to craft your LinkedIn profile. And don’t get me started on people using ChatGPT to write text messages to their dates. Just no. Then there’s the rise of Ozempic, which has meant that every other celebrity has seemed to shrink before our eyes in recent months – while the rest were busy getting facelifts. From blepharoplasty to buccal fat removal, this was the year cosmetic surgery went both extreme and mainstream. I’m all for being the best version of yourself, but when teens are talking about getting sliced open with increasing nonchalance, it makes me scared for the future. And that was before I heard about skincare for toddlers (yes, really). What else from the past 12 months would I like to see climb into a giant bin? Bonkers billionaires (and their weddings), microdosing, padel, air fryers and people who have self-diagnosed ADHD just because they’re quite scatty and want to tell you all about it. And I love a matcha latte as much as the next girl, but I can’t stand anyone who makes it their entire personality (and, no, I don’t want matcha-flavoured everything). If you thought “skibidi” and “rizz” were annoying, they have nothing on the kids’

lingo of choice in 2025. “Six sevuhnn!” is now screeched at bus stops across the land, with no one – not even teens themselves – having any idea what it means. Which is, in fact, fitting, as nonsensical gibberish is all we’ve come to expect from our politicians of late, whether it’s Kemi Badenoch or Rachel from Accounts. That said, there were a few glimmers of greatness in 2025 and they came in unexpected places – the Coldplay Jumbotran, I’m looking at you. I wanted to loathe Dubai chocolate and thought it sounded like overhyped silliness. Then I tried some and now consume a bar a night (so, on second thoughts, maybe I wish I’d never heard of it). Likewise, Gen Z’s alcopop of choice, BuzzBallz – so fun! So colourful! So drunk-making! Culturally, I’ll remember this as the year of KPop Demon Hunters, which my five-year-old daughter is now bored of, while I’m still singing all the songs. Hopefully that will get my Spotify Wrapped age down from 84 next year (sadly, not a joke). A KPDH sequel is now in the works, along with a whole new batch of trends, fads and topics of conversation to rage bait us over the coming months. But until then, please no more Labubus, I beg of you. F • Follow Kate on Instagram @katewills writes

elements.text: Texture, asymmetry and mystical aesthetics among Pinterest's 2026 beauty trends to watch
Pantone and WGSN reveal their 2026 Colours of the Year

Pinterest's annual Pinterest Predicts report, based on search behaviour from 600 million monthly users, found that clients increasingly seek comfort, personalisation and sensory experiences, with trends evolving 4.4 times faster than seven years ago. Textural and tactile beauty is on the rise. Searches for "jelly blush"

and "gummy bears aesthetic" point to demand for 3D nail art, playful gloss finishes and ASMR-style experiences. Asymmetric and maximalist looks, including "Glitchy Glam" and accessory-inspired styles, are also growing, alongside delicate lace detailing and fragrance layering. Salon interiors are being influenced by Neo Deco and Afrohemian aesthetics, offering ways to update spaces without major refurbishment. Meanwhile, nature-inspired and mystical trends, from opalescent finishes to forest-themed nails, are shaping immersive client experiences. Pinterest advises beauty professionals to focus on texture, escapism and individuality to meet evolving client expectations.

Pantone and WGSN/Coloro have announced two very different - and divisive - Colour of the Year predictions: Cloud Dancer, a soft, billowy white; and Transformative Teal, a blue-green shade rooted in ecological awareness and change. For beauty professionals, these two contrasting hues offer distinct creative paths for the year ahead: one centred on minimalism, calm and visual clarity, and the other on nature, regeneration and future readiness. The forecasts provide opportunities for contrasting trends across the professional beauty sector, providing inspiration for everything from salon interiors and packaging, to nail and makeup trends.
